## 3. Screen 1 — Horizon Declaration

### 3.1 Purpose

This screen presents a clean readback of everything the user defined in their Clarity Compass. The user reads it, confirms it is still accurate, and locks it in as the foundation for synthesis. It should feel like a declaration document — not a form, not a wizard step.

### 3.2 Layout Structure

**Page Header**
- Title: `Your Strategic Direction`
- Subtitle: `Review your stated vision across all horizons. Confirm to generate your strategic synthesis.`
- No back button. No tabs. Full-width single-column layout, centered, max-width ~720px for readability.

---

**Ultimate Vision Block**

Positioned at the top of the declaration, above the horizon cards. Visually distinct — styled as a pull quote or framed statement block.

Contents:
- Label: `ULTIMATE VISION`
- The user's ultimate vision statement from the Clarity Compass, displayed in full
- No editing. Read-only.

Visual treatment: light background fill (brand-consistent), left border accent, slightly larger text than body. This is the north star — it should feel weightier than the horizon cards below it.

---

**Horizon Cards**

Three cards displayed in vertical stack, full width. All three visible simultaneously on page load — no hiding, no collapse, no pagination.

Each card contains:

| Element | Content |
|---|---|
| Horizon label | `12-Month Horizon`, `24-Month Horizon`, `36-Month Horizon` |
| Target date | e.g., `Target: Q1 2027` — pulled from Clarity Compass |
| Vision statement | The user's qualitative goal for this horizon — full text, read-only |
| Growth scenario | The GV Simulator scenario attached to this horizon (name + key financial target) |
| One-line synthesis | A single platform-generated sentence summarizing what this horizon represents in plain language. Example: *"A foundation-building year focused on systematizing delivery and stabilizing financial infrastructure."* |

Card styling:
- Clean white card with subtle border
- Horizon label and target date in header row
- Vision statement in body — readable font size, no truncation
- Growth scenario displayed as a small tag or inline label
- One-line synthesis displayed in a muted style beneath the vision statement — visually distinct to signal it is platform-generated, not user-authored

---

**Refinement Link**

Below the three horizon cards, before the confirm button:

`Not what you intended? Refine your vision in the Clarity Compass →`

This is a secondary text link, not a button. It routes to `/foundations/clarity-compass`. It should not feel like a default path — it is a deliberate detour for users who want to update their vision before proceeding.

---

**Confirm Action**

A single primary button, full width or prominently centered:

Button label: `Confirm My Direction & Generate Synthesis`

On click:
- Validates that all hard dependencies are met (final check)
- If not met: surfaces dependency notice (see Section 2)
- If met: triggers synthesis generation (see Section 4) and transitions to the synthesis screen

Below the button, a single line of supporting copy:
`This locks your horizon vision as the foundation for your strategic synthesis. You can return to refine at any time.`

---

### 3.3 Interaction States

| State | Behavior |
|---|---|
| Default (dependencies met) | All cards populated, confirm button active |
| Locked (dependencies missing) | Cards show placeholder content, confirm button disabled, dependency notice visible |
| Hovered (confirm button) | Standard hover state — no special behavior |
| Clicked (confirm button) | Button enters loading state, transition to synthesis loading experience begins |

